        <div class="sidebar-refs-section">
          <p class="nav-label">On This Page</p>
          <a href="#references" class="sidebar-ref-link">References</a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <main class="main-content">

        <!-- Hero -->
        <div class="page-hero">
          <div class="tab-badge">Tab 1</div>
          <h1>Basic Rankine Cycle</h1>
          <p class="hero-sub">
            From heat to electricity: the fundamental thermodynamic cycle powering most of the world's electricity generation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 1: Why the Rankine Cycle? -->
        <section class="section" id="why-rankine">
          <h2>Why the Rankine Cycle?</h2>
          <p>
            To generate electricity, you need to spin a generator. But most primary energy sources (nuclear fission,
            combustion, concentrated sunlight, geothermal heat) produce only <em>heat</em>, not rotation. The Rankine
            cycle is the dominant thermodynamic bridge between heat and mechanical work.
          </p>
          <p>
            The key insight is <strong>phase change</strong>. When water boils, it expands to roughly 1,600 times its
            liquid volume<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup>. Channel that expanding steam through a turbine
            and you have a practical, continuous, high-power machine. Condensed back to liquid, the working fluid can be
            pumped back to high pressure at a fraction of the energy cost of compressing a gas; this asymmetry between
            pumping a liquid versus compressing a gas is what makes the cycle efficient.
          </p>
          <p>
            Unlike internal combustion engines, which convert discrete piston strokes into rotation, steam turbines
            are <em>steady-flow devices</em>. They operate at stable, continuous conditions for months at a time,
            the kind of reliability a baseload power plant demands. A single large steam turbine at a nuclear plant
            can produce over 1,000 megawatts<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>, enough electricity for
            roughly one million homes.
          </p>
          <div class="callout callout--info">
            <div class="callout-icon">i</div>
            <div class="callout-body">
              <strong>Not just for electricity.</strong> Any application needing shaft work from heat can use a
              Rankine cycle: marine propulsion, industrial drives, and spacecraft power systems have all used
              Rankine-based designs. But large-scale electricity generation is where it has no serious rival.
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: Why Water? -->
        <section class="section" id="why-water">
          <h2>Why Water?</h2>
          <p>Water is remarkably well-suited to this cycle. Its advantages are numerous and they compound:</p>

          <div class="prop-grid">
            <div class="prop-card">
              <div class="prop-title">Heat of Vaporization</div>
              <div class="prop-value">2,260 kJ/kg<sup><a href="#ref-3" class="cite">[3]</a></sup></div>
              <p class="prop-desc">
                Water absorbs an enormous amount of energy when boiling with minimal temperature change. This lets
                boilers transfer large heat fluxes efficiently and keeps the T-s diagram spanning a wide, useful range.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="prop-card">
              <div class="prop-title">Availability</div>
              <div class="prop-value">~71% of Earth's surface</div>
              <p class="prop-desc">
                Power plants site near rivers, lakes, or coastlines for cooling water. In industrial quantities,
                supply is never a constraint.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="prop-card">
              <div class="prop-title">Safety</div>
              <div class="prop-value">Non-toxic, non-flammable</div>
              <p class="prop-desc">
                A steam leak is loud and causes thermal burns, but carries no chemical hazard. This simplifies
                safety engineering dramatically versus hydrocarbon working fluids.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="prop-card">
              <div class="prop-title">Chemical Stability</div>
              <div class="prop-value">Stable to ~650&deg;C<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup></div>
              <p class="prop-desc">
                Water doesn't decompose at operating temperatures and is among the best-characterized substances
                in thermodynamics. Steam tables cover the full operating range with high precision.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="callout callout--question">
            <div class="callout-icon">?</div>
            <div class="callout-body">
              <strong>Can Rankine cycles use a different working fluid?</strong>
              <p>
                Yes: these are called <strong>Organic Rankine Cycles (ORC)</strong>. When the heat source is at
                lower temperatures, water becomes impractical: boiling at low pressures requires operating under
                vacuum, which creates significant engineering challenges. ORC systems use refrigerants or organic
                compounds (pentane, R245fa, siloxanes) that boil at lower temperatures, enabling efficient energy
                extraction from heat sources between roughly 80-350&deg;C, typical for geothermal wells, industrial
                waste heat, and biomass combustion.<sup><a href="#ref-9" class="cite">[9]</a></sup>
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 3: Where Is It Used? -->
        <section class="section" id="applications">
          <h2>Where Is It Used?</h2>
          <p>
            The Rankine cycle is not specific to nuclear power; it is the thermodynamic backbone of most
            large-scale electricity generation on Earth. Any industry that produces heat at high temperatures
            and needs to turn a generator uses some variant of this cycle.
          </p>

          <div class="app-grid">

            <!-- Nuclear Fission (featured, full-width) -->
            <article class="app-card app-card--featured">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-nuclear">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="4" fill="currentColor"/>
                    <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
                    <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" transform="rotate(60 24 24)"/>
                    <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" transform="rotate(120 24 24)"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag app-tag--featured">Most Relevant to You</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Nuclear Fission</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Boiling Water Reactors (BWR) &amp; Pressurized Water Reactors (PWR)</div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <p>
                Nuclear fission reactors generate heat by splitting heavy atomic nuclei, primarily
                uranium-235<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>. That heat boils water to drive the
                Rankine cycle. Two reactor designs dominate commercial nuclear power, and they differ fundamentally
                in how they handle this heat transfer:
              </p>

              <div class="two-col">
                <div class="reactor-box">
                  <h4>Boiling Water Reactor (BWR)</h4>
                  <p>
                    Water boils directly inside the reactor pressure vessel. That steam travels straight to the
                    turbine with no intermediate loop. The design is mechanically simpler, but the turbine handles
                    mildly radioactive steam and requires shielding and careful maintenance scheduling.
                  </p>
                  <p class="local-note">
                    Nine Mile Point Units 1 and 2, along with the neighboring James A. FitzPatrick Nuclear
                    Power Plant, are all GE BWRs situated on the shores of Lake Ontario near Oswego,
                    NY.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div class="reactor-box">
                  <h4>Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR)</h4>
                  <p>
                    Two entirely separate water loops keep the radioactive primary coolant isolated from the
                    turbine. The primary loop runs at ~155 bar<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>,
                    hot enough to boil, but the pressure prevents it. Heat exchangers called <em>steam
                    generators</em> transfer energy to a clean secondary loop that produces the turbine steam.
                    PWRs are the most common reactor type worldwide.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/power/how-reactors-work.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                NRC: How nuclear power reactors work &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Coal -->
            <article class="app-card app-card--declining">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-coal">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <!-- Irregular rock/coal lump polygon -->
                    <path d="M17 9L27 7L36 13L40 23L37 33L29 40L18 41L9 34L7 22L13 14Z"
                          fill="currentColor" opacity="0.2"/>
                    <path d="M17 9L27 7L36 13L40 23L37 33L29 40L18 41L9 34L7 22L13 14Z"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                    <!-- Facet lines giving it a chunky rock look -->
                    <path d="M17 9L23 19L13 14" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                    <path d="M27 7L23 19L36 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                    <path d="M23 19L37 33" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.35" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <path d="M23 19L9 34" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.35" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag app-tag--declining">In Decline</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Coal</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Pulverized coal boiler plants</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Coal plants burn pulverized coal in a large furnace to heat a boiler to approximately
                540&deg;C<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup>, producing high-pressure steam for the
                turbine. Coal dominated electricity generation for most of the 20th century, but the economics
                have collapsed: natural gas is cheaper per BTU, wind and solar are cheaper per kWh in most
                markets, and environmental regulations on mercury, SO&#x2082;, NO&#x2093;, and particulate
                emissions add significant compliance costs. U.S. coal electricity generation has fallen more
                than 60% since its 2007 peak.<sup><a href="#ref-4" class="cite">[4]</a></sup>
              </p>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/coal/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                EIA: Coal explained &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Oil -->
            <article class="app-card app-card--declining">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-oil">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <path d="M24 10C24 10 14 22 14 31C14 36.5 18.5 41 24 41C29.5 41 34 36.5 34 31C34 22 24 10 24 10Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                    <path d="M19 33C19 36 21.2 38 24 38" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag app-tag--declining">Rare &amp; Declining</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Oil</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Fuel oil peaker plants</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Oil-fired steam plants burn fuel oil in a boiler, mechanically the same as a coal plant but
                with liquid fuel.<sup><a href="#ref-5" class="cite">[5]</a></sup> They're expensive to operate
                and rarely run at baseload. Instead, they serve as <em>peaking plants</em>: started only during
                extreme demand periods, typically a few hundred hours per year. The <strong>Oswego Energy
                Center</strong> on Lake Ontario is a notable local example; it sits adjacent to Nine Mile Point
                Units 1 and 2 and the James A. FitzPatrick plant, making the Oswego waterfront home to one oil
                peaker and three nuclear reactors.
              </p>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/oil-and-petroleum-products/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                EIA: Oil and petroleum products explained &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Natural Gas -->
            <article class="app-card">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-gas">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <path d="M16 36C16 36 10 31 10 23C10 15 18 9 18 9C18 9 15 18 22 22C22 22 19 13 26 9C26 9 33 17 29 26C29 26 33 21 33 17C33 17 39 24 37 32C35 38 30 41 24 41C18 41 16 36 16 36Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag">Combined Cycle</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Natural Gas</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Brayton + Rankine combined cycle (CCGT)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Natural gas combined cycle plants (CCGT) stack two thermodynamic cycles in series, achieving
                thermal efficiencies of 60-64%<sup><a href="#ref-6" class="cite">[6]</a></sup>, roughly double
                that of a simple steam plant:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Brayton cycle (gas turbine)</strong>: Compressed air and natural gas combust at
                  ~1,300&deg;C<sup><a href="#ref-6" class="cite">[6]</a></sup>, driving a gas turbine directly
                  and generating electricity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rankine cycle (steam turbine)</strong>: The gas turbine exhaust (still ~600&deg;C)
                  passes through a heat recovery steam generator (HRSG), producing steam for a second
                  turbine stage.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The Rankine portion recovers energy that would otherwise escape as waste heat. You will study
                the Brayton cycle in depth in a later thermodynamics course.
              </p>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/natural-gas/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                EIA: Natural gas explained &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Concentrated Solar -->
            <article class="app-card">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-solar">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="7.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"/>
                    <line x1="24" y1="5"  x2="24" y2="13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="24" y1="35" x2="24" y2="43" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="5"  y1="24" x2="13" y2="24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="35" y1="24" x2="43" y2="24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="10.2" y1="10.2" x2="15.9" y2="15.9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="32.1" y1="32.1" x2="37.8" y2="37.8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="37.8" y1="10.2" x2="32.1" y2="15.9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <line x1="15.9" y1="32.1" x2="10.2" y2="37.8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag">Renewable</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Concentrated Solar Power</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">CSP (not photovoltaic)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                CSP plants use mirrors to focus sunlight onto a receiver, generating intense heat to drive a
                Rankine cycle.<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="cite">[7]</a></sup> This is fundamentally different
                from photovoltaic (PV) solar panels, which convert light directly to electricity with no moving
                parts and no thermodynamic cycle. Three main CSP configurations:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Power Tower</strong>: A large field of flat mirrors (heliostats) reflects sunlight
                  onto a central receiver atop a tall tower. Achieves the highest temperatures (&gt;500&deg;C)
                  and integrates well with molten salt thermal storage for generation after sunset.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Parabolic Trough</strong> (most widespread): Long curved mirrors focus sunlight
                  onto a tube at their focal line, heating a fluid that then generates steam.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Parabolic Dish</strong>: Individual dish mirrors focus sunlight at a single point;
                  often paired with a Stirling engine rather than a Rankine turbine.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.nrel.gov/research/concentrating-solar-power.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                NREL: Concentrating solar power research &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Geothermal -->
            <article class="app-card">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-geo">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <!-- Ground line -->
                    <path d="M6 31H42" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <!-- Subtle below-ground texture -->
                    <path d="M6 31C10 34 14 32 18 35C22 38 26 36 30 35C34 34 38 36 42 34"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <!-- Three steam wisps rising from ground (classic geothermal icon) -->
                    <path d="M15 29C15 29 12 25 15 21C15 21 18 17 15 13"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <path d="M24 29C24 29 21 25 24 21C24 21 27 17 24 13"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <path d="M33 29C33 29 30 25 33 21C33 21 36 17 33 13"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag">Renewable</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Geothermal</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Earth's internal heat</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Geothermal plants tap heat from within the Earth.<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="cite">[8]</a></sup>
                In high-enthalpy fields (Iceland, The Geysers in California), steam rises naturally from the
                ground and feeds directly into a turbine. In lower-enthalpy fields, hot water is brought to the
                surface and "flashed" to steam at lower pressure, or an ORC uses geothermal heat to boil a
                working fluid that vaporizes at lower temperatures than water. Geothermal's defining advantage
                over solar and wind: it provides <strong>baseload power 24 hours a day</strong>, independent
                of weather or sunlight.
              </p>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.energy.gov/eere/geothermal/geothermal-basics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                DOE: Geothermal basics &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Waste Heat Recovery -->
            <article class="app-card">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-waste">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <!-- Industrial chimney/stack -->
                    <rect x="15" y="23" width="10" height="17" rx="1.5"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"/>
                    <!-- Ground -->
                    <path d="M8 40H40" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.45"/>
                    <!-- Heat waves rising from stack -->
                    <path d="M18 21C18 21 15 17 18 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <path d="M22 21C22 21 19 17 22 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    <!-- Curved capture arrow looping from heat to right side -->
                    <path d="M24 13C29 9 37 13 37 21C37 28 33 32 30 33"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" fill="none"/>
                    <path d="M27 31L30 34L33 31"
                          stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag">Industrial</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Waste Heat Recovery</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">ORC systems for low-grade heat</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Steel mills, cement plants, glass furnaces, and refineries discharge enormous quantities of
                heat that would otherwise be lost to the atmosphere. Organic Rankine Cycle systems can capture
                this heat, even at moderately low temperatures (150-400&deg;C), and generate electricity from
                it.<sup><a href="#ref-9" class="cite">[9]</a></sup> The "fuel" is effectively free, since the
                industrial process would generate the heat regardless. Waste heat recovery simultaneously
                reduces operating costs and carbon emissions, making it one of the highest-return energy
                investments in heavy industry. The principle is straightforward: the second law says useful
                work can be extracted from any temperature differential; the question is only whether it's
                worth the capital cost to do so.
              </p>
              <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.energy.gov/eere/amo/waste-heat-recovery" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                DOE: Waste heat recovery technologies &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>

            <!-- Nuclear Fusion (featured, full-width) -->
            <article class="app-card app-card--future">
              <div class="app-card-head">
                <div class="app-icon icon-fusion">
                  <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                    <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="5" fill="currentColor"/>
                    <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="14" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4 3"/>
                    <circle cx="24"  cy="10"  r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                    <circle cx="36"  cy="31"  r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                    <circle cx="12"  cy="31"  r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                  </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <div class="app-tag app-tag--future">Emerging Technology</div>
                  <h3 class="app-name">Nuclear Fusion</h3>
                  <div class="app-type">Some designs use the Rankine cycle; others may bypass it entirely</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Commercial fusion power plants don't exist yet, but several private companies are making rapid
                progress. Their approaches to converting fusion energy into electricity differ fundamentally, and
                it's an open question whether the Rankine cycle will be part of the picture at all.
              </p>
              <div class="two-col">
                <div class="fusion-box">
                  <h4>Commonwealth Fusion Systems (CFS)</h4>
                  <p>
                    CFS is building a compact tokamak called SPARC, with a commercial plant called ARC planned
                    to follow.<sup><a href="#ref-10" class="cite">[10]</a></sup> ARC's design extracts heat from
                    a lithium blanket surrounding the plasma and uses a conventional <strong>Rankine cycle</strong>
                    to generate electricity, thermodynamically similar to a fission nuclear plant: heat in,
                    steam turbines, electricity out.
                  </p>
